✅ Number

Represents both integers and floating-point values.

let a = 10;
let b = 3.14;

console.log(typeof a); // "number"
✅ Boolean

Represents true or false.

let isActive = true;
console.log(typeof isActive); // "boolean"
✅ String

Sequence of characters.

let name = "Kuldip";
let city = 'Ahmedabad';

console.log(typeof name); // "string"
✅ null

Represents intentional absence of value.

let data = null;
console.log(data);        // null
console.log(typeof data); // "object" (JavaScript bug)
✅ undefined

Variable declared but not assigned.

let x;
console.log(x); // undefined
🔹 2. typeof Operator

Used to check data type.

console.log(typeof 10);        // number
console.log(typeof "Hello");   // string
console.log(typeof true);      // boolean
console.log(typeof undefined); // undefined
🔹 3. Type-Checking Functions
Common checks:
Array.isArray([1, 2, 3]); // true

isNaN("abc"); // true (Not a Number)

Number.isInteger(10); // true
🔹 4. "use strict"

Enforces stricter parsing and error handling.

"use strict";

x = 10; // ❌ Error (must declare variable)

Benefits:

Prevents accidental globals
Safer code
Helps debugging
🔹 5. Type Conversion
parseInt()
parseInt("100");     // 100
parseInt("100px");   // 100
parseFloat()
parseFloat("10.5");  // 10.5
🔹 6. Formatting Numbers
toFixed()

Rounds to fixed decimal places.

let num = 12.3456;
console.log(num.toFixed(2)); // "12.35"
toPrecision()

Formats to total digits.

let num = 123.456;
console.log(num.toPrecision(4)); // "123.5"
toLocaleString()

Formats based on locale.

let num = 1000000;
console.log(num.toLocaleString()); // "1,000,000"
🔹 7. String Operations
let str = "JavaScript";

console.log(str.length);        // 10
console.log(str.toUpperCase()); // JAVASCRIPT
console.log(str.substring(0,4));// Java
console.log(str.replace("Java", "Type")); // TypeScript
🔹 8. eval() Function ⚠️

Executes a string as JavaScript code.

eval("console.log(2 + 3)"); // 5

⚠️ Warning: Avoid using eval() due to:

Security risks
Performance issues
🔹 9. Quotes (Single vs Double)

Both are valid, used for flexibility.

let str1 = "Hello";
let str2 = 'World';
Nesting Example:
let msg = "He said 'Hello'";
let msg2 = 'She said "Hi"';
🔹 10. Initialization

Declaring and assigning value:

let x = 10;        // initialized
let y;             // declared only
y = 20;            // assigned later
🔹 11. Type Conversion (Explicit & Implicit)
Explicit
Number("123"); // 123
String(123);   // "123"
Boolean(1);    // true
Implicit (Coercion)
"5" + 2;  // "52"
"5" - 2;  // 3
